As of this past Friday, McCurtain county is listed as Orange level 2. This means the same procedures we were following last week will be in place, while adding that masks will be worn in PK-3 classrooms when social distancing isn‚Äôt possible. We will be utilizing traditional scheduling at this time. Thanks for your support and understanding.

post_text:
The schedule for 3rd-12th grade for the first week is listed below. Pk-2nd grade teachers will be calling and setting up appointments for days to bring your student up for orientation. We have split the alphabet into 4 even groups. We will be following this schedule during the week of August 24th ONLY. On August 31st, we will resume classes Monday- Thursday.

Monday 8/24- A through C
Tuesday 8/25- D through J
Wednesday 8/26- K through R
Thursday 8/27- S through Z

If your household has students with different last names then they will all come on the day of the oldest child's name.

The buses will run during the first week like normal.

We will be posting information and dates soon for our virtual students to receive their log in information and technology. The pick up time will be during the week of August 24th.

Information about the upcoming school year will be coming out in the morning. We will be providing information about the "Return to School Plan" and curriculum options.

Our start date for school will be August 17th for students.

Teachers will report on August 3rd to begin training for the upcoming year. The 20/21 school year will have many new exciting changes. Moving the kids back to the 17th will allow our staff to be better prepared for when students arrive.

shared_text:
Haworth Secondary
June 8 at 4:22 PM ¬∑

Beginning on Wednesday, June 10th, Haworth will begin the Summer Feeding Program. It will continue until July 16. We will be offering to go meals at the School Cafeteria. We will not have a dine in option. All meals will be picked up in a drive through format like we did in March, April and May. The meals may be picked up between 10:00 and 11:00 am. We will be offering meals at the School Cafeteria only. The students do not have to be in the vehicle at the time of pick up; however, you will have to provide the names of the students. Any child 18 or under is eligible to receive meals.

post_text:
Parents & Community,

As distance learning continues to move forward and ongoing adjustments are made, I would like to thank you for your support and encouragement that many of you have given to our administration and staff during this time. It has been without a doubt an interesting time in education and in every other area of life. During this time of adjustment it is good to know that we have the support and understanding of many who are concerned and are willing to pull together. Once again, we will continue to keep you informed and work for the good of our students as this scenario plays out. Thank you for your support and determination to continue to work together.

Go Lions!

Jason Price
SuperintendentAs

post_text:
Parents,

Any students that will be starting distance learning by using paper packets will receive them on Monday, April 13th. The following options will be available for you to receive your packets.

Option 1:

Packets can be picked up in front of the cafeteria between 11:00-12:00. Enter the open gate in front of the high school, drive around in front of the high school gym, drive to the front of the cafeteria and a staff member will bring the packet to you in your car.

Option 2:

Specific buses will run starting at 1:00 to deliver packets. If you are unable to pick up your packet at the cafeteria we will bring it to you. Please be watching for buses in your area.

Option 3:

If you ride a bus that goes to the 4-way in Idabel, or you live in Idabel, packets can be picked up between 2:30-3:00. A school suburban will be in the Catfish King parking lot with the packets.

Go Lions!

Jason Price
Superintendent

Parent & Community,

The State Board of Education met today in Oklahoma City and determined that all schools will be out for the remainder of the current school year. This also includes all extra curricular activities.

Currently, our meal program will continue into the first weeks of May. A specific cut off date will be provided at a later time.

Even though school is out, there will be distance learning required for us to participate in. This will begin Monday, April 6th. Our staff will begin the process of putting this area together. We will provide you further details of how this will work as quickly as possible.

Once again, we don‚Äôt have all the answers but as we learn more we will inform you. It is one step at a time. Continue to be safe and work together.

We will provide further information concerning upcoming academic requirements and other areas as the overall plan is organized.

Go Lions!

Superintendent
Jason Price

post_text:
Parents, Community, & Staff,

Although we are in interesting times in education it has been a privilege to watch staff, board members, community members, and businesses come together and continue to meet the challenges we face each day. First and foremost, the well-being of our students is our #1 priority. Today, while handing out meals at Haworth, Goodwater, and Tom many children received food because of the willingness of a caring group of people to serve. It can‚Äôt be done alone and for those who have served I say ‚Äúthank you!‚Äù Keep it up!

As for school itself, there are many questions that do not have answers yet as we continue to work with the Oklahoma State State Department of Education. As we receive answers we will pass them on to you as quickly as possible. Our goal is to do what is right and serve our students as well as possible as we are allowed. Continue to stay safe and work together. We will get through this!

Go Lions!

Superintendent
Jason Price

post_text:
Haworth Community,

Today we discovered a threatening message inside of our high school that caused us to evacuate the school. Although we are uncertain if it was a legitimate threat, we always hold the safety of our students and staff at the highest importance. After being notified we cleared the school and ran our buses as soon as possible. It was done in a quality manner. After the buildings were cleared with an outstanding effort from our staff, the Sheriff Department entered the facilities and performed a manual sweep of the area. Nothing was discovered. However, evidence was taken and information will be evaluated. As always, if information is received that we discover who is responsible, the highest level of action will be taken. School is a place for learning and we want to keep Haworth at the highest level possible. I hope you will continue to do your part in supporting our school as we continue to raise our standards. Thank you for your support and dedication to Haworth Public School.

Professionally,

Jason Price-Superintendent

post_text: This week we celebrated kindness week. To finish up the week we had each student write something nice on a post-it note. That something nice could be a kind word or something nice about their friend. We took all of the post-it notes and placed them on the wall for all of the kids to see. It was great to see kids go look at the wall and smile when the read the kind words. #kindness #lionpride

We are excited about school starting on August 6th! Our staff members have been working hard to get the building ready for students and are almost ready!

We have exciting changes taking place this year! In order for our students to receive the best possible education many of our grade levels will be switching classes. (Kindergarten will switch between the 2 kindergarten teachers and 4th and 5th grade will switch amongst the 4 teachers) This is a small change that will produce great outcomes for our students.

The Elementary class lists have been posted on the office doors. For confidentiality reasons we can not post the lists on Facebook. Please refrain from posting a picture of the lists on social media.

Go Lions!
